{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568837"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:22:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:22:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21404"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21404"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.04,0.26,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14273"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107506"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14273"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2025-05-01T12:02:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T19:44:53+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2025-06-30T19:44:53+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-29 15:31:01"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21404"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89986"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34920"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36549"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89986"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107506"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being reported as disruptive at a hotel social event. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His acquaintance reports possible injection of drugs several hours ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears agitated and combative. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 160/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He has dilated pupils, diaphoresis, and is hyperreflexic. He is restrained on a trolley but continues fighting against the restraints. An intravenous cannula is in situ.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous diazepam","Intravenous chlorpromazine","Intramuscular haloperidol","Intramuscular benztropine","Intramuscular promethazine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic sympathomimetic toxidrome, characterised by agitation, tachycardia, hypertension, mydriasis, and diaphoresis. These features strongly suggest intoxication with a stimulant such as amphetamines, cocaine, or synthetic cathinones. When managing sympathomimetic toxicity, benzodiazepines are the first-line agents as they effectively counteract both central and peripheral sympathetic effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous diazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it directly addresses the underlying pathophysiology of sympathomimetic toxicity by enhancing GABA-mediated inhibition, thereby reducing central nervous system excitation, autonomic hyperactivity, and the risk of seizures. The intravenous route allows for rapid onset of action and easy titration, which is crucial in managing severe agitation. Guidelines recommend 5-10 mg IV every 5-10 minutes until adequate sedation is achieved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous chlorpromazine\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for sympathomimetic toxicity. As a phenothiazine antipsychotic, it can lower the seizure threshold, potentially worsen hyperthermia through anticholinergic effects, and may cause hypotension through alpha-adrenergic blockade. These effects make it unsuitable for managing stimulant intoxication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular haloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E carries similar concerns to chlorpromazine regarding seizure threshold and hyperthermia. Additionally, first-generation antipsychotics like haloperidol can potentially worsen outcomes in stimulant toxicity due to their effects on dopamine receptors and may increase the risk of dysrhythmias, particularly when QT prolongation is present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular benztropine\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticholinergic medication primarily used for treating extrapyramidal side effects of antipsychotics. It has no role in managing sympathomimetic toxicity and could potentially worsen hyperthermia and agitation due to its anticholinergic properties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular promethazine\u003C/strong\u003E is an antihistamine with sedative properties, but it is not appropriate for sympathomimetic toxicity. Like other medications with anticholinergic properties, it may worsen hyperthermia and does not address the underlying sympathetic hyperactivity. Additionally, it can lower the seizure threshold.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intravenous benzodiazepines are first-line agents for managing sympathomimetic toxidrome due to their efficacy in reducing central and peripheral sympathetic effects","Clinical features of sympathomimetic toxidrome include agitation, tachycardia, hypertension, hyperthermia, and mydriasis","Aggressive management of agitation in sympathomimetic toxicity is paramount to prevent complications including rhabdomyolysis and hyperthermia"],"references":["Life in the Fast Lane. Sympathomimetic toxidrome. Available at: https://litfl.com/sympathomimetic-toxidrome/","Therapeutic Guidelines [eTG complete]. Toxicology and toxinology: stimulant toxicity. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Deranged Physiology. Sympathomimetic toxicity. Available at: https://derangedphysiology.com/main/required-reading/environmental-injuries-and-toxicology/Chapter-531/sympathomimetic-toxicity","Schaffer DH, Richards JR. Sympathomimetic Toxicity. [Updated 2025 Feb 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430757/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21404"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89986"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T19:44:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T19:45:22+09:30","number":9,"notes":"Updated references.","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-06-30T19:44:53+09:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-14273-9.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T145250Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=cdb0771e0e817c9e57349068d3c813f0de6098e64cef3c7cae170266e144e71b"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type"